articles.title: Amazon-backed housing development breaks ground east of Seattle
articles.summary: Transit-oriented project with affordable units planned for Redmond, Washington

leadMedia.caption: More than half of 152nd Overlakes 233 units are reserved for renter households earning between 60% and 80% of the areas median income. (SHW)

articles.body:
Real estate developers Johnson & Carr and Stellar Holdings have started a transit-orient apartment project in Redmond, east of Seattle, thats financially backed by Amazons affordable housing equity fund.

The locally based firms broke ground on 152nd Overlake, a 233-unit slated to open in August 2027 near Sound Transits Overlake Village station.

The project, designed with 2,700 square feet of retail space and 120 units reserved for lower-income renters, is the latest development to receive funding from Amazon aimed at boosting affordable housing in greater Seattle, a region that has among the nations highest average apartment rents and home prices.

The tech giant committed $15.6 million in low-cost financing from its housing equity fund that looks to help build and preserve affordable housing in the Puget Sound and other regions where the firm has big corporate operations, including the Nashville, Tennessee, and Washington, D.C., areas.

Amazon-funded housing project takes shape in Seattle's Othello neighborhood
Nitze-Stagen has finished the concrete podium of the eight-story Trace 4001 multifamily development.
Randyl Drummer

Social

Amazons support has been instrumental in enabling us to offer below-market rents in a high-opportunity, transit-oriented location, Johnson & Carr President Tyler Carr said in a statement.

With more than half of the units designated as affordable for the next 99 years to qualifying renters, this development will help residents live near jobs, transit, and essential services in one of the Puget Sound regions fast-growing areas, added Senthil Sankaran, Amazon Housing Equity Fund managing principal.

The 120 units for lower-income renters are aimed at households earning between 60% and 80% of the areas median income, which is equal to between $63,638 and $84,850 in annual income, according to the statement.

The 152nd Overlake project, designed with a mix of studio, one- and two-bedroom units, will have underground parking and common areas that include a fitness room, resident lounge and shared workspaces, rooftop deck and bike storage.

For the record

Stearns Bank also contributed financing to the project designed by SHW and being built by W.G. Clark Construction.
